<quiz><question number="37">
        <prompt>What was the impact of the "holding company" innovation?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Allowed corporations to own stock in other companies</option>
            <option letter="b">Restricted business growth</option>
            <option letter="c">Protected small businesses</option>
            <option letter="d">Promoted competition</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>The holding company structure, pioneered by Standard Oil, allowed corporations to legally own stock in other companies, facilitating the creation of large business combinations.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question number="38">
        <prompt>How did the development of the Pullman sleeping car affect rail travel?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Made long-distance rail travel more comfortable</option>
            <option letter="b">Decreased ticket prices</option>
            <option letter="c">Reduced train speed</option>
            <option letter="d">Limited passenger capacity</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Pullman sleeping cars revolutionized rail travel by making long-distance journeys more comfortable, though they also created a system of racial discrimination in service positions.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question number="39">
        <prompt>What effect did the "bucket shop" system have on stock trading?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Created gambling-like speculation on stocks</option>
            <option letter="b">Improved market stability</option>
            <option letter="c">Protected small investors</option>
            <option letter="d">Regulated stock prices</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Bucket shops allowed small investors to speculate on stock prices without actually buying stock, creating a gambling-like atmosphere that destabilized markets.</explanation>
    </question>
    <question number="40">
        <prompt>What was the significance of the "vertical integration" strategy?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Control of all stages of production and distribution</option>
            <option letter="b">Focus on single product lines</option>
            <option letter="c">International trade expansion</option>
            <option letter="d">Employee profit sharing</option>
        </options>
        <answer>a</answer>
        <explanation>Vertical integration, exemplified by Carnegie Steel, involved controlling all stages of production and distribution to reduce costs and eliminate middlemen.</explanation>
